From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Fruit Jam Linux <fruitjam-linux@local>
Date: Thu, 18 Jun 2026 08:05:00 -0400
Subject: [PATCH] misc: size Fruit Jam usbhost TX buffer for XInput

wili8jam's known-working Fruit Jam USB host configuration enables 64-byte HID
and XInput endpoint buffers.  The Linux PIO bridge already captures 64-byte IN
packets, and the HCD can now submit interrupt/bulk/control OUT transfers, but
its encoded TX buffer was still sized for early setup and boot-keyboard probes.

A full-speed 64-byte OUT payload is encoded as sync + PID + 64 payload bytes +
CRC16: 68 raw bytes.  In the worst case, USB bit stuffing adds one bit after
each six consecutive one bits, and the PIO encoding stores four two-bit bus
symbols per byte.  That needs fewer than 160 encoded bytes after EOP and
alignment, so use a 192-byte buffer.  This avoids truncating or overflowing
XInput/HID OUT reports such as the Xbox 360 wireless receiver init packets once
enumeration reaches those endpoints.
---
 drivers/misc/fruitjam_usbhost.c | 6 +++++-
 1 file changed, 5 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/drivers/misc/fruitjam_usbhost.c b/drivers/misc/fruitjam_usbhost.c
--- a/drivers/misc/fruitjam_usbhost.c
+++ b/drivers/misc/fruitjam_usbhost.c
@@ -59,6 +59,10 @@
 #define FJ_USBHOST_HCD_IN_NAK_ATTEMPTS 16u
 #define FJ_USBHOST_HCD_IDLE_SLEEP_MS	20u
-#define FJ_USBHOST_TX_ENCODED_MAX	96u
+/*
+ * Enough for a worst-case bit-stuffed full-speed DATA packet carrying a
+ * 64-byte HID/XInput payload: sync + PID + payload + CRC16 + EOP/alignment.
+ */
+#define FJ_USBHOST_TX_ENCODED_MAX	192u
 #define FJ_USBHOST_RX_BYTES_MAX		72u
 #define FJ_USBHOST_TX_DMA_CHANNEL_DEFAULT 2u
 #define FJ_USBHOST_PROBE_SUMMARY_MAX	512u
